Explaining Portuguese exam results using SHAP¶

The goal of this homework was to explain the results of students from their lifestyles and life situations. Using the conclusions from the previous homework, I use the Portuguese dataset only, since stronger relations were visible in it and there is also more data available. I found that the values given by shap match my intuition about the variables better than what I was able to find in the last homework by only looking at the plots. The model that is being explained is mostly XGBoost with the exception of the last subtask, where XGBoost is compared with a Random Forest model.

Subtask 4¶

I found the requested observations. The first plot is from dalex:

We can see, as was also visible in the last homework, that student receiving extra educational support is quite strongly correlated with the student having worse results. It is visible here - the first student doesn't receive educational support and this variable is much less important in their case. There are much more students that don't receive the support than those who do, and among those that don't there is much bigger variety in exam results than among those that do. Number of previous failures showed the greatest correlation with the result among the non-categorical variables and the two schools present in the dataset had significantly different scores. The fact that in the second case the father being a teacher is so important also makes sense - probably it's quite rare for a child whose father is a teacher to perform poorly.

And now the shap results:

It looks similar to the previous case, but this time health is more important than father being a teacher in the second case.

Subtask 5¶

The variable for which I was able to find that it had different attributions for different observations is the age of a student equal to 19. The results for dalex first again:

Now shap:

Some reason for this difference in the two samples could be the fact, that older students have more difficult topics, so if they don't study a lot, then when they get older their results decrease. But that is only one viable reason, there could most likely be many others.

Subtask 6¶

In general the results are a bit different, but I wasn't able to observe anything drastic. It's mostly that sometimes one feature is a bit more important in one than in the other. Let's look at the specific example of the two random samples from subtask three.

We can observe that they look pretty similar. One interesting hypothesis may be that shap from shap module attributes more importance to studytime=2 (which also showed up in the example in the previous exercise).

Appendix¶

Contains the Python code used to create the above raport

Dataset¶

This dataset contains the data about the scores of students of two different school in Portugal in math and Portuguese. The goal is to predict the final score of a student, using information about their lifestyle and background. I am going to focus only on predicting G3 - according to the description of the problem G1 and G2 are highly correlated with G3.

Data preparation¶

Split into features and targets. The same as in the previous homework, we focus on predicting the final result only.

In [213]:
port_x = portuguese_df.drop(['G3', 'G2', 'G1'], axis = 1)
port_y = portuguese_df[['G3']]

Categorical variables need to be encoded.

In [214]:
def encode_categorical(df):
    df = df.copy()
    
    df = df.replace({'GP': 0, 'MS': 1})
    df = df.replace({'F': 0, 'M': 1})
    df = df.replace({'U': 0, 'R': 1})
    df = df.replace({'LE3': 0, 'GT3': 1})
    df = df.replace({'A': 0, 'T': 1})
    df = df.replace({'no': 0, 'yes': 1})
    
    onehot_features = ['Mjob', 'Fjob', 'reason', 'guardian']
    df = pd.concat([df, pd.get_dummies(df[onehot_features])], axis=1)
    df = df.drop(onehot_features, axis=1)

    return df
In [215]:
port_x = encode_categorical(port_x)

There is little data available. There is much more data about results from portuguese than from math. For that reason, we are going to train our models using both datasets at once and then test them separately.

Homework implementation¶

Below the code used for solving each of the required homework tasks is contained. Only XGBoost is used with the exception of the subtask 7.

Subtask 1¶

We train two models XGBoost and random forest model. We train on the whole dataset, since there isn't much data and it shouldn't matter for the explanations.

In [216]:
models = {
    'Boosting': XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror'),
    'Forest': RandomForestRegressor()
  }

for name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(port_x, port_y.values.ravel())
